{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md && sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md && sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/architecture.md && sed -n '1,260p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/adr.md && sed -n '1,220p' .workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json\"","aggregated_output":"# Product Spec\n\nProduct: WakeTask (`com.keen.waketask`)\n\nWakeTask is a wake-accountability iPhone app focused on sustained wakefulness, not just alarm dismissal. The core model is a two-phase wake flow: mission-gated dismissal followed by post-dismiss wake verification.\n\n## Research Evidence\n\n- Users report autopilot alarm dismissal and relapse sleep within minutes.\n- Reliability trust is fragile; users keep backup alarms due to fear of missed firing or mission failure loops.\n- Competitive demand is validated for mission alarms, but incumbents are frequently criticized for ad clutter, pricing shock, and brittle flows.\n- Highest-confidence opportunities from the matrix are:\n  - post-dismiss wake assurance loop\n  - mission safety rails with fallback\n  - visible reliability telemetry and readiness checks\n  - travel-proof strictness profiles\n  - trust-first wake UX and transparent monetization\n\n## User Journeys\n\n1. Setup and first alarm\n- User grants notifications.\n- User creates an alarm and selects a mission chain.\n- App validates mission inputs at setup (especially scan targets).\n- User sees readiness state before sleep.\n\n2. Alarm firing and dismissal\n- Alarm fires at scheduled time.\n- User must complete mission chain to dismiss.\n- If mission cannot complete (invalid target/unavailable condition), app routes to accountable fallback mission.\n\n3. Post-dismiss stay-awake verification\n- After dismissal, app runs wake checks at +3, +7, and +12 minutes.\n- Missed/failed check triggers escalating re-alarm behavior.\n- Session is marked successful only when all required checks pass.\n\n4. Morning trust review\n- User opens morning reliability log.\n- User sees event timeline and fallback usage for each alarm.\n\n5. Travel context\n- User switches to a travel profile with resilient mission stack and fallback options.\n\n## MVP Scope\n\nIn scope (v1):\n- Mission-gated alarm dismissal with chain support (math, memory, motion, scan).\n- Setup-time mission validation, including scan target verification UX.\n- Accountable fallback mission path that avoids trap states.\n- Post-dismiss wake-check loop at +3/+7/+12 with escalation.\n- Per-alarm reliability log with user-visible timeline fields.\n- Context profiles: weekday, weekend, travel.\n- Trust-first wake UI: large controls, minimal decision load, non-creepy tone.\n- Transparent pricing and permissions messaging.\n\nOut of scope (v1):\n- Sleep-stage analytics platform.\n- Social/competitive wake community features.\n- Wearable-dependent wake logic.\n- Broad wellness content feed.\n\n## Boilerplate Reuse\n\nImplementation must extend `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution` and reuse platform modules. No rewrite of foundational infrastructure without explicit ADR approval.\n\nMust reuse:\n- `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj`\n- `Config/App.xcconfig`\n- `Packages/Core`\n- `Packages/Networking`\n- `Packages/Storage`\n- `Packages/Auth`\n- `Packages/Payments`\n- `Packages/AI`\n- `Packages/FeatureSettings`\n- `Packages/Localization`\n- `Packages/DesignSystem`\n- `CompositionRoot`\n\n## Design Direction\n\n- Principle: “3:30am-safe UX”.\n- Alarm-critical screens prioritize large targets, low cognitive load, and high-contrast clarity.\n- Progressive friction model: light cognitive -> moderate cognitive -> physical validation.\n- Tone policy: neutral/strict coach options; no manipulative or intimate notification language.\n- Wake-critical paths avoid ad-like clutter and accidental-tap traps.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. Mission completion rules\n- `math`: user completes configured number of problems; each answer validated before advance.\n- `memory`: user reproduces sequence with exact-match threshold.\n- `motion`: user achieves configured motion signal threshold.\n- `scan`: user scans validated target; if unavailable, fallback mission is required.\n\n2. Post-dismiss schedule and outcome\n- Wake checks trigger at +3, +7, +12 minutes after dismissal timestamp.\n- Any missed/failed check triggers escalation re-alarm.\n- Session success requires all scheduled checks to pass.\n\n3. Fallback safety protocol\n- If primary mission input is invalid/unavailable, app must present fallback mission within one user step.\n- Fallback route cannot dead-end or trap user in unrecoverable loop.\n- Fallback usage is logged in reliability telemetry.\n\n4. Reliability telemetry fields (per alarm)\n- Required: `alarm_scheduled_at`, `alarm_fired_at`, `dismissed_at`, `wake_check_results`, `fallback_used`, `profile_used`.\n- Morning log renders these fields in a user-readable timeline.\n\n5. Permissions behavior\n- Notifications requested before first active alarm enablement.\n- Camera requested only when scan mission is configured.\n- If camera denied, user gets non-camera fallback mission option and clear recovery path.\n\n6. Trust and policy constraints\n- No credential values or environment variable dumps in logs/reports.\n- Secret checks may emit boolean presence only.\n- No guaranteed-wake claims in UI/metadata; language must reflect iOS platform limits.\n\n7. Quality gates\n- Blocking checks: `xcodebuild build`, `xcodebuild test`, SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, secret scanning, App Store string audit.\n\n## Appium Exploratory QA\n\nRequired exploratory run outcome file: `reports/ios/appium-exploratory-report.json`\n\nPass contract:\n- Real simulator/Appium run executed unless workflow input explicitly sets `defer_appium: true` and documented blocker exists.\n- Explorer taps every reachable enabled control in MVP flows with bounded-depth traversal.\n- Report includes:\n  - `ok` (boolean)\n  - `buttons_tapped` (integer)\n  - `screens_visited` (integer)\n  - `crashes` (integer)\n  - `failures` (integer)\n  - `failures_detail` (array)\n- Pass threshold:\n  - `ok=true`\n  - `crashes=0`\n  - `failures=0`\n  - `buttons_tapped >= 25`\n  - `screens_visited >= 8`\n\n## App Store Readiness\n\n- 4.3 differentiation narrative must be explicit: two-phase wake model + reliability log + mission safety rails.\n- Metadata and in-app strings must avoid clone-like generic claims and avoid “guaranteed wake” wording.\n- Privacy disclosure must match actual permission usage and explain camera/notification purpose clearly.\n- Release hardening requires string/metadata audit pass before TestFlight handoff.\n\n## Definition of Done\n\nSee `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`. All checklist items are blocking unless explicitly marked deferred with owner and date.\n# Definition of Done\n\n- [ ] Product scope lock: implementation matches `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md` MVP scope and excludes listed non-goals.\n- [ ] Boilerplate reuse proof: no unauthorized rebuild of Auth, Payments, AI, Networking, Storage, Localization, DesignSystem, or CompositionRoot.\n- [ ] Swift concurrency safety: Swift 6 strict concurrency remains enabled and builds cleanly.\n- [ ] File size guard: all production and test Swift files are <= 400 lines.\n- [ ] Alarm mission engine implemented for math, memory, motion, and scan paths.\n- [ ] Mission setup validation implemented, including scan target pre-validation.\n- [ ] Fallback safety protocol implemented with non-trapping recovery path.\n- [ ] Post-dismiss wake checks implemented at +3/+7/+12 minutes with escalation behavior.\n- [ ] Stay-awake success rule implemented: session is successful only when all required wake checks pass.\n- [ ] Reliability telemetry persisted per alarm with required fields:\n  - `alarm_scheduled_at`\n  - `alarm_fired_at`\n  - `dismissed_at`\n  - `wake_check_results`\n  - `fallback_used`\n  - `profile_used`\n- [ ] Morning reliability log UI displays telemetry timeline for each alarm event.\n- [ ] Context profiles (weekday/weekend/travel) are selectable and affect mission behavior.\n- [ ] Permission gating implemented: notifications pre-alarm, camera only for scan mission, denial recovery path present.\n- [ ] Trust tone constraints enforced: no relational/intimate creepy copy in wake-critical notifications.\n- [ ] Pricing and permission copy is transparent and non-surprising in wake flow.\n- [ ] Security hygiene check passes: no hardcoded secrets, no secret-like values in artifacts.\n- [ ] Secret handling check passes: scripts only emit credential presence as true/false, never values.\n- [ ] CI quality script includes and passes: `xcodebuild build`, `xcodebuild test`, SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, secret scan, App Store string audit.\n- [ ] Workflow evidence exists at `reports/ios/ios-quality-report.json` and indicates all blocking checks passed.\n- [ ] Appium exploratory evidence exists at `reports/ios/appium-exploratory-report.json` and satisfies thresholds (`ok=true`, `crashes=0`, `failures=0`, `buttons_tapped>=25`, `screens_visited>=8`) unless explicit deferral is approved.\n- [ ] App Store hardening audit passes with no banned wording and explicit 4.3 differentiation in release metadata.\n- [ ] macOS/Xcode execution evidence is attached for build/test (or explicit approved deferral documented).\n- [ ] Final review fanout signs off product fidelity, iOS architecture, security/privacy, code quality, QA evidence, and release readiness.\n- [ ] Any deferred item includes: reason, owner, unblock condition, and target date.\n# WakeTask Architecture\n\n## Purpose\nBuild WakeTask as an extension of `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` with no foundational rewrites, preserving strict Swift 6 concurrency, CI quality gates, and App Store differentiation through the two-phase wake model.\n\n## System Topology\n1. `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj` remains the integration shell and target graph owner.\n2. `CompositionRoot` wires app services, repositories, and feature routes into the app scene.\n3. Feature packages implement WakeTask domain flows behind protocol boundaries owned by `Packages/Core`.\n4. iOS app target and UI tests validate end-to-end alarm, mission, fallback, and wake-check flows.\n\n## Boilerplate Module Mapping\n- `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj`\n  - Keep as root project; add WakeTask feature targets/schemes only as needed.\n- `Config/App.xcconfig`\n  - Keep as source of bundle id/environment toggles (`com.keen.waketask`) and build flags.\n- `Packages/Core`\n  - Owns domain models/protocols for alarms, mission chain, wake-check schedule, reliability timeline, and context profile selection.\n- `Packages/Networking`\n  - Reused for remote config/pricing copy fetches and optional telemetry upload; no alarm-critical behavior depends on network availability.\n- `Packages/Storage`\n  - Persists per-alarm reliability telemetry fields (`alarm_scheduled_at`, `alarm_fired_at`, `dismissed_at`, `wake_check_results`, `fallback_used`, `profile_used`) and mission/profile configuration.\n- `Packages/Auth`\n  - Retained unchanged for account/session if enabled; wake-critical execution remains functional without blocking on auth.\n- `Packages/Payments`\n  - Retained for transparent paywall and entitlement checks; monetization messaging kept outside alarm-critical interaction steps.\n- `Packages/AI`\n  - Retained for non-critical assistant/personalization surfaces only; never required for alarm firing, dismissal, fallback, or wake verification.\n- `Packages/FeatureSettings`\n  - Hosts alarm defaults, strictness profiles (weekday/weekend/travel), permission recovery affordances, and tone/policy options.\n- `Packages/Localization`\n  - Owns all user-facing strings, including App Store 4.3 differentiation language and anti-\"guaranteed wake\" constraints.\n- `Packages/DesignSystem`\n  - Implements 3:30am-safe components (large targets, high contrast, low cognitive load), avoiding ad-like clutter.\n- `CompositionRoot`\n  - Registers implementations for mission engine, fallback resolver, wake-check scheduler, reliability logger, and screen entry points.\n\n## WakeTask Feature Slices\n1. Alarm Setup Slice\n- Configure alarm + mission chain.\n- Validate mission inputs at setup (scan target pre-validation, camera permission checks).\n\n2. Alarm Execution Slice\n- Fire alarm locally.\n- Enforce mission-gated dismissal (math, memory, motion, scan).\n- Route to fallback mission in one step on unavailable/invalid primary mission conditions.\n\n3. Post-dismiss Verification Slice\n- Schedule wake checks at +3, +7, +12 minutes from dismissal time.\n- Escalate via re-alarm on missed/failed checks.\n- Mark session successful only if all required checks pass.\n\n4. Trust & Review Slice\n- Render morning timeline from persisted reliability fields.\n- Expose fallback usage and profile used for trust transparency.\n\n## Dependency Direction\n1. `DesignSystem`/`Localization` are leaf presentation dependencies.\n2. `FeatureSettings` and WakeTask feature UIs depend on `Core` protocols and DesignSystem.\n3. Repository implementations depend on `Storage` and optionally `Networking`.\n4. Monetization/auth adapters depend on `Payments`/`Auth` but never invert into `Core`.\n5. `CompositionRoot` performs final assembly and injects protocols into app entry points.\n\n## Concurrency and Reliability Constraints\n- Isolate alarm-state mutation behind actor-backed services.\n- Use main-actor view models and async protocol APIs for mission evaluation and wake checks.\n- Keep mission and wake-check scheduling deterministic and resumable after app relaunch.\n- Ensure fallback routing cannot dead-end by requiring an always-available fallback mission type.\n\n## Testing and Evidence Plan\n- Unit tests: mission validators, fallback resolver, wake-check scheduler timing, reliability timeline mapping.\n- Integration tests: full dismissal->wake-check escalation path and permission denial recovery.\n- UI tests/Appium exploratory: tap every reachable enabled control, include trust log/profile switching routes.\n- Blocking quality gates: `xcodebuild build`, `xcodebuild test`, SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, secret scan, App Store string audit.\n\n## Non-goals Guardrail\n- No rebuild of Auth/Payments/AI/Networking/Storage/Localization/DesignSystem/CompositionRoot.\n- No sleep-stage analytics platform, social wake community, or wearable-required core logic in MVP.\n# ADR: WakeTask on SwiftAIBoilerplatePro\n\n- Status: Accepted\n- Date: 2026-05-14\n- Deciders: iPhone App Factory architecture consensus\n- Context: `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/spec.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/definition-of-done.md`, `.workflow/iphone-app-factory/quality-bar.json`, architecture candidates in repository context\n\n## Decision\nWakeTask will be implemented by extending `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro` modules and composition boundaries, with no foundational module removals in MVP.\n\n## Decisions by Module\n1. `SwiftAIBoilerplatePro.xcodeproj`: retain as project root and scheme owner.\n2. `Config/App.xcconfig`: retain as configuration source of truth.\n3. `Packages/Core`: retain and extend for wake domain protocols/models.\n4. `Packages/Networking`: retain for non-critical remote data and telemetry.\n5. `Packages/Storage`: retain for persistent reliability timeline and alarm state.\n6. `Packages/Auth`: retain unchanged; optional for account-linked features.\n7. `Packages/Payments`: retain unchanged; supports transparent monetization.\n8. `Packages/AI`: retain unchanged; restricted to non-alarm-critical UX.\n9. `Packages/FeatureSettings`: retain and extend for context profiles and policy settings.\n10. `Packages/Localization`: retain for policy-safe and differentiated copy.\n11. `Packages/DesignSystem`: retain for 3:30am-safe interaction patterns.\n12. `CompositionRoot`: retain and extend for dependency injection and feature wiring.\n\n## Rationale\n- Satisfies explicit boilerplate-reuse constraints in spec and quality bar.\n- Minimizes delivery risk by reusing validated infra and CI assumptions.\n- Preserves App Store 4.3 differentiation by focusing changes on WakeTask-specific behavior (two-phase wake model, fallback safety rails, reliability telemetry) rather than generic foundation rewrites.\n\n## Dependency Order (required for any future removal proposal)\nAny proposal to remove a module must preserve this order and replace interfaces from the bottom up:\n1. `Core` protocol contracts remain stable first.\n2. Replace implementation adapters (`Storage`, `Networking`, `Auth`, `Payments`, `AI`) behind those contracts.\n3. Rebind in `CompositionRoot`.\n4. Validate UI consumers in `FeatureSettings`, `Localization`, `DesignSystem` surfaces.\n5. Re-run full quality gate and App Store language audit.\n\n## App Store 4.3 Consequences of Module Removal\nIf a module is removed or replaced without preserving differentiated WakeTask behavior:\n- Risk of clone-like implementation increases if UX degrades into generic alarm/paywall templates.\n- Loss of reliability logging or fallback transparency weakens differentiation claims and can trigger 4.3 scrutiny.\n- Replacing Localization/DesignSystem without policy controls increases risk of banned “guaranteed wake” or generic/derivative metadata language.\n- Removing Payments/Auth/AI foundations ad hoc can force rushed custom scaffolding that looks commodity and raises rejection risk during metadata + in-app review consistency checks.\n\n## Candidate Tradeoff Summary\n- Smallest-surface architecture bias is accepted for MVP speed and reduced regression area.\n- Extensible pipeline ideas are accepted only where they do not introduce new foundational frameworks or replace boilerplate modules.\n\n## Consequences\n- Positive: faster delivery, lower integration risk, cleaner audit trail for DoD and final review fanout.\n- Negative: some future extensibility is deferred to post-MVP ADRs.\n- Follow-up: any future module-removal or deep replacement requires a new ADR with migration plan, dependency-order proof, and explicit 4.3 impact analysis.\n{\n  \"appDir\": \"apps/waketask-iphone\",\n  \"appName\": \"WakeTask\",\n  \"bundleId\": \"com.keen.waketask\",\n  \"boilerplateRepo\": \"SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro-Distribution\",\n  \"target\": \"TestFlight-ready iPhone app handoff\",\n  \"required\": [\n    \"research uses App Store reviews, Reddit, competitors, and iOS design references\",\n    \"spec candidates are generated independently and merged conservatively\",\n    \"Spec Kitty mission is recorded\",\n    \"SwiftAIBoilerplatePro is extended instead of rebuilding platform infrastructure\",\n    \"Swift 6 strict concurrency is preserved\",\n    \"production and test Swift files stay under 400 lines\",\n    \"SwiftLint, SwiftFormat, Qlty, and secret scanning are wired as blocking gates\",\n    \"xcodebuild build and xcodebuild test run in the macOS lane\",\n    \"Appium/XCUITest exploratory tapper clicks every reachable enabled button/control\",\n    \"App Store 4.3 hardening checks release strings and metadata\",\n    \"Mobbin, if used, is pattern research only and credentials remain in environment variables\",\n    \"credential availability may be checked only as true/false presence; secret values must never be printed, logged, or written to artifacts\",\n    \"agents must not run environment dump commands such as env, printenv, set, export, or declare -x\",\n    \"final review fanout must approve product fidelity, iOS architecture, security, quality, QA, and release readiness\"\n  ],\n  \"forbidden\": [\n    \"hardcoded secrets\",\n    \"printing environment variables or credential values in logs\",\n    \"running env, printenv, set, export, declare -x, or echoing secret-like variables\",\n    \"writing API tokens, passwords, cookies, OAuth credentials, or base64 auth blobs to workflow artifacts\",\n    \"fake fixture-only research without marking the limitation\",\n    \"rebuilding auth, payments, AI, storage, networking, localization, settings, or design system without ADR approval\",\n    \"declaring iOS validation complete without macOS or GitHub Actions evidence\",\n    \"skipping Appium exploratory evidence unless allow_macos_deferred is explicit\"\n  ]\n}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/Packages/DesignSystem/Sources/DesignSystem/Tokens/BrandConfig.swift && sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/Config/App.xcconfig && sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/Config/Secrets.example.xcconfig && sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/Generated/Configuration.swift\"","aggregated_output":"import SwiftUI\n\n/// Brand configuration for customization\n/// \n/// Buyers can modify these values to customize the app's branding.\n/// Changes here will be reflected throughout the app.\npublic struct BrandConfig {\n    \n    /// App display name shown in UI\n    public static let appDisplayName = \"SwiftAI Pro\"\n    \n    /// Accent color for highlights and CTAs\n    public static let accentColor: Color = DSColors.primary\n    \n    /// SF Symbol name for default avatar\n    public static let avatarFallbackSymbol = \"person.circle.fill\"\n    \n    /// App icon background color (for generated icons)\n    public static let appIconBackground: Color = DSColors.primary\n    \n    // MARK: - Customization Guide\n    \n    /*\n     HOW TO CUSTOMIZE YOUR BRAND\n     ============================\n     \n     1. App Display Name:\n        Change `appDisplayName` to your app's name\n        Example: \"MyAI Assistant\" or \"ChatBot Pro\"\n     \n     2. Accent Color:\n        Option A: Update the Primary color in Colors.xcassets\n        Option B: Set accentColor to a custom Color:\n            public static let accentColor = Color(red: 0.2, green: 0.6, blue: 1.0)\n     \n     3. Avatar Symbol:\n        Browse SF Symbols app and pick an icon:\n        Examples: \"sparkles\", \"brain.head.profile\", \"message.fill\"\n        Update `avatarFallbackSymbol` with the symbol name\n     \n     4. Color Scheme:\n        Edit Resources/Colors.xcassets to customize:\n        - Primary (brand color)\n        - BubbleUser (user message bubble)\n        - BubbleAssistant (AI message bubble)\n        - TextPrimary, TextSecondary (text colors)\n        - Background, Separator\n     \n     5. Typography:\n        Modify DSTypography in Typography.swift:\n        - Change font sizes\n        - Switch font design (.default, .rounded, .serif, .monospaced)\n        - Adjust line spacing\n     \n     All changes automatically apply throughout the app with no additional code changes needed.\n     */\n}\n\n// General app-level build settings you want in VCS\nPRODUCT_NAME = WakeTask\nSWIFT_VERSION = 6.0\nIPHONEOS_DEPLOYMENT_TARGET = 17.0\nASSETCATALOG_COMPILER_GLOBAL_ACCENT_COLOR_NAME = AccentColor\n\n// Include secrets if present (local only)\n#include? \"Config/Secrets.xcconfig\"\n// Copy this file to Config/Secrets.xcconfig and fill these values.\n// See supabase/DEPLOYMENT_GUIDE.md for setup instructions\n\n// Supabase Configuration\n// Get these from: https://app.supabase.com → Project Settings → API\nSUPABASE_URL = https://YOUR-PROJECT-REF.supabase.co\nSUPABASE_ANON_KEY = YOUR_PUBLIC_ANON_KEY\n\n// Google Sign In (Optional)\n// Get from: https://console.cloud.google.com → APIs & Services → Credentials\n// Create iOS OAuth Client ID, then paste the client ID here\n// GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID = YOUR_IOS_CLIENT_ID.apps.googleusercontent.com\n\n// RevenueCat Configuration  \n// Get from: https://app.revenuecat.com → Project Settings → API Keys\nREVENUECAT_API_KEY = YOUR_RC_KEY\nRC_ENTITLEMENT_ID = pro\n\n// AI Proxy Configuration (Supabase Edge Function)\n// After deploying the Edge Function, use: https://YOUR-PROJECT-REF.supabase.co/functions/v1\nPROXY_BASE_URL = https://YOUR-PROJECT-REF.supabase.co/functions/v1\nPROXY_PATH = /ai\n\n// OneSignal Push Notifications (Optional)\n// Get from: https://onesignal.com → Settings → Keys & IDs\n// Leave commented out if you don't want push notifications\n// See docs/integrations/OneSignal.md for setup guide\nONESIGNAL_APP_ID = YOUR_ONESIGNAL_APP_ID\n// This file is auto-generated from Config/Secrets.xcconfig\n// Run 'bash scripts/update-config.sh' after updating Secrets.xcconfig\n// Default placeholder values allow clone-and-run with MockAuthClient and EchoLLMClient\n\nimport Foundation\n\n/// Application configuration loaded from Config/Secrets.xcconfig\n/// This ensures configs work in all build types (Debug, Release, Archive, TestFlight, App Store)\nenum AppConfiguration {\n    static let SUPABASE_URL = \"https://placeholder.supabase.co\"\n    static let SUPABASE_ANON_KEY = \"placeholder-key-for-debug-mode\"\n    static let REVENUECAT_API_KEY = \"placeholder_rc_key\"\n    static let RC_ENTITLEMENT_ID = \"pro\"\n    static let PROXY_BASE_URL = \"https://placeholder.supabase.co/functions/v1\"\n    static let PROXY_PATH = \"/ai\"\n    static let ONESIGNAL_APP_ID = \"placeholder_onesignal_app_id\"\n    \n    /// Check if a configuration value is available (not a placeholder)\n    static func isConfigured(_ key: String) -> Bool {\n        switch key {\n        case \"SUPABASE_URL\": return !SUPABASE_URL.contains(\"placeholder\") && !SUPABASE_URL.contains(\"YOUR\")\n        case \"SUPABASE_ANON_KEY\": return !SUPABASE_ANON_KEY.contains(\"placeholder\") && !SUPABASE_ANON_KEY.contains(\"YOUR\")\n        case \"REVENUECAT_API_KEY\": return !REVENUECAT_API_KEY.contains(\"placeholder\") && !REVENUECAT_API_KEY.contains(\"YOUR\")\n        case \"PROXY_BASE_URL\": return !PROXY_BASE_URL.contains(\"placeholder\") && !PROXY_BASE_URL.contains(\"YOUR\")\n        case \"ONESIGNAL_APP_ID\": return !ONESIGNAL_APP_ID.contains(\"placeholder\") && !ONESIGNAL_APP_ID.contains(\"YOUR\")\n        default: return true\n        }\n    }\n}\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_6","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/Resources/privacy.md && sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/Resources/terms.md && sed -n '1,260p' apps/waketask-iphone/SwiftAIBoilerplatePro/Resources/subscription_terms.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Privacy Policy\n\n**Last Updated:** October 8, 2025\n\n## Information We Collect\n- Account info (email, name)\n- Usage data\n- AI conversations\n- Device info\n\n## How We Use It\n- Provide services\n- Process AI requests\n- Improve app\n- Send notifications\n\n## Data Sharing\n- **AI Providers:** Your prompts go to AI services (OpenAI, Anthropic)\n- **Analytics:** Anonymous usage stats\n- **Apple:** Payment processing\n\n## Your Rights\n- Access your data\n- Delete your account\n- Export conversations\n- Opt-out of marketing\n\n## Security\n- Encryption in transit\n- Secure storage\n- Regular audits\n\n## Children\nNot for users under 13.\n\n## Changes\nWe'll notify you of policy updates.\n\n## Contact\nEmail: privacy@yourapp.com\n\n## GDPR (EU)\nYou have right to data portability, erasure, and complaint filing.\n\n## CCPA (California)\nWe don't sell your data. Contact us for data disclosure.\n\n*Customize this policy with legal counsel.*\n\n# Terms of Service\n\n**Last Updated:** October 8, 2025\n\n## 1. Acceptance of Terms\nBy using this app, you agree to these terms.\n\n## 2. Use License\nPersonal, non-commercial use only.\n\n## 3. User Accounts\nYou are responsible for your account security.\n\n## 4. AI Content\nAI-generated content may not always be accurate. Verify important information.\n\n## 5. Privacy\nSee our Privacy Policy for data handling practices.\n\n## 6. Prohibited Uses\nNo illegal, harmful, or abusive content generation.\n\n## 7. Subscription\nSubscriptions auto-renew. Fees are non-refundable except as required by law.\n\n## 8. Termination\nWe may terminate accounts for Terms violations.\n\n## 9. Limitation of Liability\nWe are not liable for damages from app use.\n\n## 10. Changes\nWe may update these terms. Continued use = acceptance.\n\n## Contact\nEmail: support@yourapp.com\n\n*Consult legal counsel to customize for your needs.*\n\n# Subscription Terms\n\n**Last Updated:** October 8, 2025\n\n## Plans\n- Monthly: [Price]/month\n- Annual: [Price]/year\n\n## Payment\n- Via Apple App Store\n- Auto-renews unless cancelled 24h before period end\n- Manage in iOS Settings → Subscriptions\n\n## What You Get\n- Unlimited AI conversations\n- Premium AI models\n- Priority responses\n- Cloud sync\n- No ads\n\n## Free Trial\n- New users may get free trial\n- Cancel anytime during trial\n- No charge until trial ends\n\n## Cancellation\n- Cancel anytime in iOS Settings\n- Access until end of paid period\n- No partial refunds\n\n## Refunds\n- Request via Apple Support or reportaproblem.apple.com\n- Apple decides refund eligibility\n\n## Changes\n- We may modify features or pricing\n- 30-day notice for price changes\n\n## Data After Cancellation\n- 30 days to export data\n- Then deleted per Privacy Policy\n\n## Contact\nEmail: support@yourapp.com\n\n*Ensure compliance with Apple's guidelines.*\n\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
